# The use of nix

**CRITICAL: This project uses nix to manage the development environment.**

**YOU MUST ALWAYS prefix commands with `CURSOR_DEV=true nix develop -c`:**

**For Cloud VM setup, see the `cloud-agent-setup` rule.**

```bash
CURSOR_DEV=true nix develop -c <command>
```

# Development Environment Setup

## Starting the Development Environment

**IMPORTANT**: Always assume that the developer has already started all necessary services using:

```bash
pnpm sut
```

This command starts:

- Backend (with auto-reload on Java code changes via Gradle continuous build)
- Frontend (with hot module replacement on Vue code changes)
- Mountebank (mock external services)

**CRITICAL: All services automatically restart/reload when code changes are made.**

**DO NOT tell developers to restart `pnpm sut` after making code changes!**

- Backend: Uses Gradle continuous build (`-t` flag) which automatically detects changes, recompiles Java classes, and hot-reloads them into the running Spring Boot application
- Frontend: Uses Vite with Hot Module Replacement (HMR) for instant Vue component updates
- Developers should NEVER need to manually restart services during development

**If services are not running or if you need to suggest starting them**, recommend running `pnpm sut` in a separate terminal first. But once running, DO NOT suggest restarting after code changes.

**Unsure if SUT is running?** Run **`CURSOR_DEV=true nix develop -c pnpm sut:healthcheck`**. If not OK, run **`CURSOR_DEV=true nix develop -c pnpm sut:restart`**, or start **`pnpm sut`** if nothing was listening. Do **not** tell people to restart `pnpm sut` after normal code edits. **Cloud VM** (no Nix): same **`pnpm sut:healthcheck`** / **`pnpm sut:restart`** from repo root; **`sut:restart`** needs **`lsof`** — see **`cloud-agent-setup`**.

## Local MySQL and Redis (nix shell hook and process-compose)

- **`scripts/nix_shell_hook.sh`** (via **`flake.nix`** shellHook) uses **`process-compose.yaml`** for supervised **`mysql`** and **`redis`**. It runs **`setup_mysql_env`** / **`setup_redis_env`** from **`scripts/shell_setup.sh`** (nix **`mysql84`** and **`redis`** paths come from **`flake.nix`**).
- **MySQL:** When **`CURSOR_DEV` is unset**, if **nothing is listening on TCP 3309**, the hook runs **`process-compose -f process-compose.yaml up -D mysql`**, waits for readiness, then applies **`scripts/sql/init_doughnut_db.sql`**. If **3309 is already in use**, the hook **does not** start or restart MySQL.
- **Redis:** When **`CURSOR_DEV` is unset**, if **nothing is listening on TCP 6380**, the hook runs **`process-compose -f process-compose.yaml up -D redis`**, then **`check_redis_ready`**. If **6380 is already in use** (including a stray non–process-compose **`redis-server`**), the hook **does not** start supervised Redis; free the port or stop the other process first.
- With **`CURSOR_DEV=true`** (typical agent invocations), those blocks are **skipped**. Start MySQL and/or Redis explicitly (see below) or use an interactive shell without **`CURSOR_DEV=true`** when appropriate.

**Stop MySQL and Redis** (detached process-compose project and supervised processes):

```bash
CURSOR_DEV=true nix develop -c process-compose down
```

(From repo root; same as **`process-compose down`** inside an active nix dev shell.)

**Manual start** when the port is free and **`MYSQL_*`** / **`REDIS_*`** are set (after **`setup_mysql_env`** / **`setup_redis_env`** in **`scripts/shell_setup.sh`**, i.e. inside **`nix develop`**):

```bash
process-compose -f process-compose.yaml up -D mysql
process-compose -f process-compose.yaml up -D redis
```

With only **`nix develop -c`**, set **`MYSQL_*`** / **`REDIS_*`** the same way as the hook (e.g. source **`scripts/shell_setup.sh`** and call **`setup_mysql_env`** / **`setup_redis_env`** with the nix package paths) before **`process-compose up`**, or use an interactive **`nix develop`** / **`direnv`** session once with **`CURSOR_DEV` unset** so the hook starts them.

**Debug / restart — MySQL:** **`mysql/mysql.log`** (also **`$MYSQL_HOME/mysql.log`**); **`mysqladmin ping -h127.0.0.1 -P3309`**; **`CURSOR_DEV=true nix develop -c process-compose attach`**; **`CURSOR_DEV=true nix develop -c process-compose process logs mysql`**. If MySQL misbehaves: **`process-compose down`** or **`process-compose process stop mysql`**; if **3309** is still held, **`pkill mysqld`** / **`lsof -i :3309`**, then **`process-compose -f process-compose.yaml up -D mysql`**.

**Debug / restart — Redis:** **`redis/redis.log`** (**`$REDIS_LOG_FILE`**); **`redis-cli -p 6380 ping`**; **`CURSOR_DEV=true nix develop -c process-compose process logs redis`**; stop only Redis: **`CURSOR_DEV=true nix develop -c process-compose process stop redis`**. If **6380** is still held, **`lsof -i :6380`** and stop the stray **`redis-server`**, then **`process-compose -f process-compose.yaml up -D redis`**.

**direnv “taking a while” / post-hook pause:** After **`Environment setup complete!`**, Nix may still print **`removing profile version …`** while updating the dev profile (not the shell hook). **`.envrc`** sets **`DIRENV_WARN_TIMEOUT`** (e.g. **`120s`**); if the **5s** warning still appears, set **`warn_timeout`** in **`~/.config/direnv/direnv.toml`**. **`dev_setup.sh`** skips **`corepack`** + **`pnpm install`** when the workspace fingerprint is unchanged ( **`corepack use`** alone was still running a full install). The hook sets **`PC_DISABLE_TUI=1`** before **`process-compose`**. More: **`CLAUDE.md`** (Local MySQL / Redis / direnv).

## Running Commands in Terminal

**For Cloud VM setup, see the `cloud-agent-setup` rule.**

Always use `CURSOR_DEV=true nix develop -c` prefix for commands (e.g., `CURSOR_DEV=true nix develop -c pnpm frontend:test`).

When deleting files, instead of using `rm -f` or `rm -rf` prefer to use `trash` instead provided by `trash-cli` from flake.nix packages.

# Development preferences

## High Cohesion

It is the top priority to keep high cohesion all the time.

- Minimize the duplicate and make sure the same concept has one representation acroess the whole system
- The code should have good mapping to the ubiquitous business domain
- Thing belong together should be placed together or close by, so that they are easy to use

## Keep it simple

- DO NOT follow the defensive programming style
- Use the simplest solution and minimum code to achieve what the prompt asked to do.

## Documentation

- DO NOT add historical documentation, comments about past implementations, or completed task lists
- Code readers only care about the current state, not development history
- Exception: Temporary requirement documents in the `ongoing/` folder are allowed for active development
